The '''Kordofan sparrow''' ('''''Passer cordofanicus'''''), also known as the '''Kordofan rufous sparrow''', is a [[Old World sparrow|sparrow]] found only in southwestern Sudan and adjacent border regions of South Sudan and Chad.<ref>{{cite web|author=BirdLife International|year=2010|url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=32620&m=0|title=Species factsheet: ''Passer cordofanicus''|access-date=24 June 2010}}</ref> It is frequently considered a subspecies of the [[Kenya sparrow]], which in turn is considered a subspecies of the [[great sparrow]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kirwan|first=Guy M.|year=2008|title=Studies of Socotran Birds III. Morphological and mensural evidence for a 'new' species in the Rufous Sparrow ''Passer motitensis'' complex endemic to the island of Abd 'Al Kuri, with the validation of ''Passer insularis'' Sclater & Hartlaub, 1881|journal=[[Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club]]|volume=128|issue=2|pages=83–93}}</ref>

